s the character ot J\n.u i w i. .u if slle will. We suggest that a\nthe people and the spirit that con-! b\ncommittee o the Commercial Club\ntrels that makes communities of\n.and the Civic Association be appoint-\nsuccess and permanency. Florida is I\n,t'd lo co-operate with Major Tillman\nbig enough and has enough land to\nu i in securing an exhibit that w l be\nmake a great many such communi-l,\n..truly representative of our sect on.\nties, and the spirit ot harmony and a, f\n.Such an exhibit will cost but little\nco-operation should be preached andl.\n,1.,! ,lnie an(' effort and will he worth\ni'.., i 'J drirwuc:, ill ui uri\nI ctotn chall ha Knilt tin in u K\nM.IU.1UI lOBIISST, 1 Ulies-Ulliuu.\n.X:MX,K:::' i\nJ I\nis our motto. Let\nj creased price is paid, is reprehensible,\ns \"jlfor if drives people away from here\nHfflf PRD5PER1TY\nT j\nj\nY.\nA i\nI\nI\nt\n.............v-..-.,v;..;,.;:..:.\nI The san,e Birls wh0 spent 50-000.-\ni 000 last year for chewing gum con-\nsumed $250,000,000-worth of ice\ncream and smeared over their faces\nj and- persons $7 50,000,000 worth of\ncosmetics and perfumery, while we\nj men -smoked only $800,000,000\nworth of cigaretts and $510,000.000\nworth of cigars. And yet some of us\nhad enough left to pay income tax.\nTimes-l'nion.\nRay Payne, manager and owner of\nthe Hotel Punta Gorda, has publish\ned and is distributing a very neat\nfolder telling of the attractions of\nthis section. Mr. Payne knows the\nvalue of advertising and this year his\nappropriation for this purpose\ni WOUM Decome tne leading town of\nthe west coast south of Tampa.\no-\nHave you noticed the fine and dell-\ncate texture of the paper on which\nj That's strange, for its market value\nlls now greater than the good bond\niPaPers on whlcn we used to prin: pur\nbusiness men's stationery a tew years\nL ru.o,' ie Ltn. ,n\nns of the county to aid him in\n,Katherl a fo.\nFlorida Fair that will\n\nnone, and he should\nbe second to\nreceive the\n\nDDMltIM(n IV I rru.\nAccording to apparently reliable\nreports, some owners ol runta Gorda\nY j town lots are pursuing a very un\nj. jwise policy, not only asking prices\nthat are really too high, but even\nraising these prices when they are\naccepted by people wanting to build\nion them. Several instances of sucTi\nconduct have been related; and, if\nthey are all true, as seems likely,\nthey have prevented the building of\nat least four dwellings, one of which\nwould hae cost $7,000.00.\nAfter the owners have named\nthe prices of the lots they have for\nsale and the prices have been accept\nin good faith by intending purchasers'\nwho wish to build on them, to \"back\nout\" and refuse to sell unless an in-\nand gives them cause to talk against\nthe town. It also tempts those who\nfeel a real interest in the building\nup of the town, to suggest to the tax\nassessors the policy of assessing the\n.high-priced lots at the prices asked\nfor them. This may be the only way\nin wnicn tne evn.ot winch we are\ncomplaining can be corrected. The\nlots, as a general tning, are given in\niur luxauun at less man nail tne\nI prices asked for them.\nIf we wish the town to build up\nand the tax rate thereby reduced, we\nmust put reasonable prices on vacant\nlots suitable for dwellings; and,\nwhen the prices are acer7,;,.,i by those\nwho want the lets lor building pur-\nIpor-ee, stick to the pi ici-s first named\njand not demand higher prices.\n\nWHAT .HE\n.'AltMP.U WANTS\nThere is support here and support\nthere for various other planks\nplank:; radical and planks conserva\ntivebut we think that on the\nwhole, the following is what the ma\njority of farmers AT THIS TIME\nwant from Congress:\nAmendment or intrepretation of\nthe anti-trust laws which will make\nX I It legal for the farmer to engage\ny!jn collective marketing.\nI Strengthening of the Federal Farm\nLoan System.\nj. i Interslate commerce legislation\ni making compulsory the honest ad-\ni vert ism;: and labeling of woolen\nfabrics, food and drugs.\nDevelopment of inland waterways\nwith ocean outlets.\nEnactment of co-operative credit\nplans to provide funds for fanners.\nNational control of packers.\nImmigration laws which will main-\n1 tain American standards of citizen-\nI ship.\ni Operation of air nitrate plant by\ngovernment or lease for purpose of\nproviding cheap fertilizer.\nThe appropriation of fund's to\npermit Department of Agriculture to\nmake studies of cost of production\nof farm products.\nDisapproval of any system which\ndenies to the individual the right\nt0 work in any pIaee where his in\ndustry is needed and at any wage\nwhich is satisfactory to him.\nTHF NEW YEAR.\nThe New Year is close at hand.\nThe cartoonists and picture boys\ngenerally will represent 1921 as a\nbaby, but we like to forecast it as a\nWOMAN we don't say a \"beautiful\"\nwoman, because all women are\nbeautiful.\nWe would like to see '21 typify\nWOMANHOOD for good and suffi\ncient reasons. One is that the com\ning year would have no interest what\nu,ver ,n Wftr or the tinf,B of war\nThis old world has had its complete\n(ill of deadly conflict during the de\ncade just clqsed and if the WOMEN\ncould have their way there'd never\nbe another on this footstool of the\nLord.\nIf 1921 were a WOMAN, the world\nwould see more religion and more\nof the good things that come out of\nit. The cynics and Bolshevists and\nexploiters bf mankind generally may\nsneer all they like at religion, but\nCod in the form we civilized people\nknow Him, or in some other form,\nhas been a comfort and a high in\nspiration to untold billions in the\npast and' He will be again to untold\nbillions in the future. The earth\nneeds a great revival of real religion\nin 1921.\nIf our New Year is anything like\nWOMAN, we will see more co-operation\nin the real tihings of life and\nmuoh more gentleness and human\nsympathy and love in 1921 than for\na generation. The vice of hate has\nencircled the world and inflicted its\nwound on countless hearts. Only\nhuman sympathy, kindness and love\nwill heal the deadly hurts that the\nhuman race has suffered.\nWe repeat; let's typify the New\nYear as a WOMAN.\no\nHEW Ml 1. 1, Kit IS RIGHT.\nThe Rev. Frank It. Miller, pastor\nof the. First Baptist church of\nChicago, one of the most fashionable\nin the city, has resigned his pastorate\nand withdrawn from the ministry.\nThe world war and service among\nthe soldiers in camps, he says, des\ntroys his former ideals of Christian\nity and so, r.fter 22 years in the\nministry, he quits with creeu shatter\ned and faith submerged.\n\"I have come to believe,\" he said,\n\"that the church imposes restrictions\non a minister tnat other wholesomely\nreligious men do not have to con\ntend with. There are standards of\nChristianity in the church that I be\nlieve are purely fictitious. I cannot\nbring myself to believe that because\na man plays cards, dances and at\ntends the theatre he is a pagan.\n\"For some time past I have been\nconscious of a repugnance toward\nevangelistic methods and the super\nficial standards of the church. I have\nfound just as good Christians out\nside the church as Inside.\n\"The center of culture in America\ntoday is not the church, but the edu\ncational institutions.\"\nThe Rev. Miller is not alone in the\nconviction that tiie churches have\nadopted and endeavor to impose up\non t'heir membership standards that\nare purely fictitious and that because\na man or woman who dances, plays\netirds, goes to the theatre and other\nwise acts like a human, he or she\nIs not necessarily a pagan.\nThere are many thousands of good\nChristians w.ho are not members of\nany church and who never darken\ntheir doors simply because they are\nunwilling to sacrifice their individu\nality and the right to live their lives\nas their own consciences direct and\nendeavor to live according to the\nchurch discipline, which sets up su\nperficial standards.\nThe church, instead of growine\nand widening its influence, is losing\nground every day and it will continue\nto do so until the puritanical con\nscience fixers, who write, revise and\namend the discipline, realize that by\nsimply saying that this or that is\nwrong they cannot make you and I\nbelieve it when our common sense\nand conscience tell us there is no\nharm in a thing.\nAs. an exchange says, \"it is evident\nhowever, that this generation is in for\nI sonnking by the professions! re\nformer unless we si; ight low,' on it\nand say as the little girl told her\nmother who threati ucd to spank her\n\"You can't do it; I'm sittin' or. it!\nSTATED-PRESS\nSince Joe and Sid are no longer\npartners and exposures are the order\nof the day, we would like for Joe to\ntell just how much money he really\ndid collect from the liquor dealers for\nSid's campaign some four years ago.\nEnlighten us Joe, for Sid has never\ntold. Pensacola News.\nThe Sanford Herald says the rea\nson so many people are going to San\nford to live is that the merchants of\nthat city advertise so liberally. The\nunderlyiag idea is that advertise\nments not only pay the merchants\nthemselves but help the town by giv\ning it the air of prosperity and prog\nress. We believe this to be good log\nicGainesville Sun.\nSizing up a Town.\nTampa business men and civic as\nsociations might do well to take the\nyardstick of efficiency and measure\ntheir town in accordance with the\nplan proposed by t'he University of\nKansas.\nThe university has formulated a\nset of ten tests for a town, believing\nthat each of the points named is ab\nsolutely essential for the rounded out\nmodern city or town. These ten\npoints are: Attractiveness, health\nfulness, education, people, recreation,\nliving, accessibility, business, employ\nment and progressiveness.\nLooking them over one arrives at\nthe conclusion that none may be\nomitted or slighted without injtiry to\na community. All are essential, and\neach one is a part of the balanced\n'.v'hole which makes the city or town\nwhere the best is none too good for\nits people and their visitors. Tampa\nTribune.\nSuggestions for Legislature\nThe Times suggested a few davs\nsirfce-that among the first duties of\nthe next legislature was the adoption\nof an equitable reapportionment, to\ngether with some provision for the I\nprocuring of a statewide system of\ngood roads.\nWhile mentioning these twa im\nportant essentials, we did not mean to\nhave the inference drawn that these\nreforms were the only ones that\nshrfuld receive the attention of the\nSolons at Tallahassee. There are\nothers of hardly less importance.\nThe present blind and co'ufiisinir\nform of ballot should be changed. If\nthe primary object of voting is to\nget at the will of the people, then the\npresent bailot Is admiiahly ar!aatcd\n(o defeat that enu. o nre&iic lo\nln- voter a ballot contaiiir Tj to\n100 names without any distinction\nwhatever, except as to th o dices or\nwhich the candidates ar running, is\nto make confusion worse confour.ded\nTo require him to make a wire selec-\nI THE LAKELAND LAUNDRY I\nAlter being completely destroyed by\nfire several months ago, is agaiii\nready to serve you better than ever\nbefore. Complete new eculment.\nThe finest latindry in the South.\niamHBHi\nVRSSA JONES'\nFor that which has passed and\ngone, let us feel thankful.\nThe New Year is lure let us lmil\nit with joy a return of prosperity\nthe light of brighter days hop,-, of\na rosy future may we merit a con\ntinuation of the rapport accorded us\nin the past.\nA. P\nGrocer and Confectioner\nEDITORIALS\ntion from she mass of unknown\ni names in a very Htnlttid tunc, is tor\n!most voters an absolute Impossibility\nland results in giving nr the whoi.'\n'tning in despair, or marking intlis\ncriminately a lot of names, without\nreference to what parly thuy belong\nor what principles thsy rrpiesent.\nThe legislature should give the peo\nple a ballot with a separate column\nfor each party. Then the voter who\nwishes to vote a straight ticket can\nmark his cross at the head of hi\nballot, and the whole thing is dom\nin a moment. We venture the asser\nlain that not one voter in a hundred\ncan do it with the present form of\nballot, and make no mistakes. n\nwould facilitate counting also.\nThe \"no fence\" law is rapidly com\ning to the front as an issue, because\nof the growing importance of the\ngrower, the trucker and small farm\ner. The democratic slogan of \"Equal\nrights to all, special privileges to\nnone,\" is meaningless so long as spe\ncial privileges are granted to cattle\nowners, who are far from being in\nthe majority in this state, and whose\nI proportion of qualified voters Is be\nI coming less every year. The present\nifriw is a reminiscence of conditions\nj which have long since passed by, and\nshould be changed to conform with\npresent and future development.\nThese are a few of the issues that will\nconfront the coming legiclatuie.\nUpon the manner in which they arc\ndealt with will depend the judgement\nof the people upan that bo;- -Tampa\nTribune.\nI ABSOLUTELY RELIABLE I\nSERVICE!\nn all makes of cars r\nfrom n Pierre-Arrow X\nto a Ford. j\nVEARS O F EXPElti 10XCE\nEnables us to give X\nyou (Irst-class work. y\nNo hulf-hnuded work X\ndone. f\nSTAKTIXt; AM MtJHTING y\nSFSTEMS REPAIRED AM) X\nBATTERY. WORK RONE.\nGive us a trial and S\nsee how hard we'll X\ntry to please vou. Z\nx\nTHE MAIN STREET I\nGAR AG El\nM. T. Willis, Frop. X\nPUNTA OORDA, FLA. X\nBARBER SHOP\nY Y la\nEff 1 I\nM AJ\n1 A","height":"27652","width":"18252"}}
